<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-A_3PZzNL4GTwvU27q7qFTg" name="service_development_lifecycle_models,_NiIGsIYNEd6L7PopHG7zng" guid="-A_3PZzNL4GTwvU27q7qFTg" changeDate="2010-08-20T10:59:46.171-0700" version="7.5.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    IBM's service lifecycle model contains four major activity groups:&amp;nbsp; Model, Assemble, Deploy, and Manage.&amp;nbsp; The&#xD;
    four Rational SOMA 2.9 practices&amp;nbsp;all support the &quot;Model&quot; (earliest) portion of the lifecycle.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    The&amp;nbsp;practices&amp;nbsp;can be used to support a number of service development lifecycle models,&amp;nbsp;three of which&#xD;
    are described below.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Enterprise-Scope Service Initiative&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    In this case, an organization most likely maintains its business models and service models as Enterprise-level assets&#xD;
    -- or, at least at the level of significant autonomous business units.&amp;nbsp; These are used as inputs to any individual&#xD;
    service development project.&amp;nbsp; Business models are created and are controlled by an organization-level team of&#xD;
    business analysts.&amp;nbsp; Projects can create project-specific service models.&amp;nbsp; Project-level contributions are&#xD;
    brought into the organization-level model&amp;nbsp;using a governed review and approval process.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    Here, we have three lifecycles.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            The business models are evolved separately, using &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.bus.use_case_driven_business_modeling.base-ibm/guidances/practices/use_case_driven_business_modeling_7F800BA4.html&quot; guid=&quot;_RO-zgDN6Ed6_nLybut0Zyw&quot;>Practice: Use Case Driven Business Modeling&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and other appropriate&#xD;
            techniques.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            Service development projects build their project-specific content by executing the three Rational SOMA 2.9&#xD;
            service-related practices to support the &quot;Model&quot; aspect of the service lifecycle.&amp;nbsp; Other techniques are&#xD;
            used to support Assemble, Deploy, and Manage.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            A well-governed content harvesting and approval lifecycle is executed to bring new content into the&#xD;
            organization-level service model.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    The interactions of lifecycles 2 and 3 are illustrated and discussed further in &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../core.tech.common.extend_supp_soa-ibm/guidances/guidelines/service_model_2E0C5D3C.html&quot; guid=&quot;_lc5vgGsLEd6dX9uDBR7y4Q&quot;>Guideline: Evolving the Service Model&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    The other two lifecycle models are&amp;nbsp;collapsed versions of the first.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Enterprise-Scope Business Modeling, Project-Scope Service Development&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    In this case, we have two lifecycles.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            The business models are evolved separately.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            Services are specified and developed to support initiatives at the project (or sub-organization) level. The&#xD;
            three Rational SOMA 2.9 service-related practices are executed to support the &quot;Model&quot; aspect of the service&#xD;
            lifecycle.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    Here, there is no governed harvesting of new service-related content back into an organization-level service&#xD;
    model.&amp;nbsp; There could (should) be attempts to create service-based assets that can be reused by others, but&#xD;
    governance around reuse still is weak.&amp;nbsp; This lifecycle model might be found in organizations that are performing&#xD;
    initial SOA pilots.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Project-Scope Business Modeling and Service Development&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    This would pertain mainly to the earliest projects in an organization that is attempting to move to business-driven&#xD;
    service development.&amp;nbsp; The assumption is that any business models are high-level at best, and service development&#xD;
    is in its infancy.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    For these very earliest projects, business modeling would need to be an integral part of project execution.&amp;nbsp; So,&#xD;
    there is one overall lifecycle, which includes the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            Business modeling workflows to build the business-oriented artifacts that are essential inputs into Service&#xD;
            Identification&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
            A service development workflow, which uses all three of the service-related practices&amp;nbsp;of Rational SOMA 2.9&#xD;
            to support the &quot;Model&quot; aspect of the service lifecycle.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    The IBM Rational SOMA 2.9 Workflow is project-oriented.&amp;nbsp; It can be adapted, with appropriate additional workflows&#xD;
    and/or workflow elements, to support larger-scoped services initiatives.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
